  "title": "Die Juden und Europa",
  "story": [
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "4c131a91387d1099",
      "text": "[[Gerhard Scheit]], Der blinde Fleck der Kritischen Theorie und der Primat der Außenpolitik\n"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "bbd13e7db30fa95e",
      "text": "As far as the relationship of critical theory to the concrete question of Jewish sovereignty is concerned, in certain respects the constellation of the 1930s was repeated in the late Horkheimer. In his essay [[Die Juden und Europa]] (The Jews and Europe), completed in the first days of September 1939, he had wanted to recognize the problem he believed to see in the existence of a Jewish state in his notes in the accommodation of the Jews in the Diaspora: settling in with the existing; leniency in the face of the damage to bourgeois democracy; flirting with the powers of reaction, as long as it was not too openly anti-Semitic. The Jews thus betrayed their best traditions, they had \"once been proud of abstract monotheism, the rejection of belief in images, the refusal to make a finite into an infinite.\" Their distress today \"refers them back to this. The disrespect for a being that spreads itself into a god is the religion of those who, in the Europe of the Iron Heel, do not refrain from turning their lives to the preparation of the better one \"3."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "6273f2387697cd4d",
      "text": "The moment of truth in these remarks is the warning against the appeasement that the Western states had practiced toward Germany for so long and to which assimilating had to mean a catastrophe for the Jews. [[Gershom Scholem]], who himself had suspected something of this catastrophe since his youth, nevertheless regarded Horkheimer's text as \"a wholly useless product\" - and in it a reprint of Marx's article on the Jewish question, as he told Benjamin, who had asked him for his opinion: The comparison with Marx's essay was not only obvious, but Horkheimer had wanted to write this essay again, mutatis mutandis, \"for the situation 100 years after Marx (which did not exactly put the wisdom of that - repugnant - essay in the brightest light, as much as it was fashionable to quote it at times).\" Obviously, Scholem reminded here the determination of the Jews to the sphere of circulation, which Horkheimer seems to base the need for assimilation, according to his diagnosis, on the \"self-interest\" and \"haggling\", in which the young Marx had seen the \"worldly reason and cultus of Judaism\". But in essence, his polemic is aimed at Horkheimer's complete failure to recognize the real situation of the Jews in the face of National Socialism. The adaptation of Marx's Jewish Question, he argues, as \"an encouragement to the Jews in the Second World War ... rat-less like ghost speech\".4 Thus, Horkheimer seemed to want to explicate his famous dictum: \"But whoever does not want to speak of capitalism should also be silent about fascism\" by addressing it to the Jews of all people: \"Practical adaptation may be inevitable for the individual, the concealment of the contrasts between the concept of man and capitalist reality deprives thinking of any truth. ... The confusion has become so general that the less truth aims at the supposed practice, the greater its practical dignity. \"5 Ghost speech could become that because the appeal not to desist from turning one's life to the preparation of the better presupposes what can no longer be presupposed at all for the Jews: to survive. Thus, if the practical adaptation of the individual in order to merely survive does not enter into thinking itself, the contrasts between the concept of man and capitalist reality become conceptual ghosts. "
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "89aa0458b8956398",
      "text": "In a letter to Adorno, Scholem was much more diplomatic about Horkheimer's essay, but wrote that he no longer believed \"that the social sciences had anything relevant to contribute\" on the subject of anti-Semitism. Horkheimer's essay also merely reinforced his conviction \"that here, unfortunately, only the metaphysicians have anything useful to say on the matter.\" 6 What Scholem meant here becomes clear in the passage from Horkheimer's essay, which states that the Jews \"as agents of circulation\" have been \"disempowered\" by the Fuehrer state because the modern structure of the economy puts the whole sphere largely out of course; they are therefore only \"hit as the first victims by the dictates of the rulers, who take over the function that has fallen out.\" Thus, the hatred of Jews belongs to the phase of fascist rise, but in the totalitarian order itself anti-Semitism will find a natural end.7"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "5131371f8bcf7420",
      "text": "Such ghost speech, which was only understood by those who believed they could continue to hope for revolution, soon had to become the central problem of critical theory itself, challenging metaphysics. It turned out that anti-Semitism, unlike any other prejudice, even a racist one, raises the question of totality in nuce by answering it with annihilation - the question of how the unity of society is established in consciousness as well as in politics. This shows the weakness of the concept of state capitalism with which Horkheimer, following [[Friedrich Pollock]], tries to grasp the totalitarian order and according to which it is in principle possible for the state, whether in the New Deal of Roosevelt's USA or in the economic miracle of Hitler's Third Reich, to eliminate the sphere of circulation. As if it could be completely annulled in Germany without at the same time, as [[Karl Kraus]] already knew, reducing \"the life of the state, of the economy, of the cultural exercise to the simplest formula\": \"that of annihilation \"8 - not of the rule of man over man, whose formula has become the law of value, but of annihilation aimed at the \"total enemy\". To this formula, which the concept of state capitalism did not know, then also belongs that in the process whoever stands in the way or puts himself in the way can still be included in varying degrees as an aspect of that total enemy at any time."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "5abadcd247b8445d",
      "text": "Only in the \"Elements of Anti-Semitism\" from the Dialectic of Enlightenment of 1944 is the 'metaphysical' challenge that Scholem ironically hints at taken seriously - as also in Sartre's Réflexions sur la question juive, whose \"Portrait of the Anti-Semite\" was written around the same time. Metaphysics means, not least, that the subject matter itself does not at all develop like a mere (natural) scientific problem, but rather in the reflection on how to think and act (possible) at all, which precedes the sciences. In other words: The appeal to the Jews, which Horkheimer wrote down in 1939, believed himself to be further secured by Marx's categorical imperative as far as the existential judgment on society was concerned; he did not yet know anything about it, nor could he have known that the reality of National Socialism would force a new one and thus metaphysical questions would return, which seemed to have been buried long ago with Hegel's Weltgeist, i.e.: resolved materialistically with Marx's critique of political economy. It is hardly by chance that the categorical imperative after Auschwitz should then find itself formulated in the part of the Negative Dialectic that bears the title \"Meditations on Metaphysics\"."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "743007ae205adc6d",
      "text": "In the extermination aimed at the Jews, anti-Semitism no longer shows itself as the necessarily false consciousness - describable in sociological terms - of those who believe to perceive that the Jews are at home in the sphere of circulation. Since they want to see in those identified as agents of circulation, beyond all sociological attribution, at the same time the abstract side of capital indispensably embodied, and in this embodiment a worldwide conspiracy, their hatred of the Jews is precisely the epitome of the whole as the untrue; Not one of the aspects of this whole like racism, but the utmost, total consequence of the dialectic of enlightenment, of the transformation of the outmoded reason into modernized barbarism - so that the new imperative must be directed to what can be directly opposed to the deadly threat of the Jews as long as the dialectic of enlightenment continues."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "1f3c194037ff96d5",
      "text": "It is true that in the \"Elements of Anti-Semitism\" there is still the economistic derivation of anti-Semitism from the fact that the sphere of circulation is \"on the wane\"; likewise, it is reduced to a function for the fact that the \"ruled\" continue to affirm domination - and many a later speculative remark as to whether there are still anti-Semites or that hatred of the Jews could be replaced by hatred of any other population group may have its origin here. But derivation and reduction are now in a changed context. The perspective on the possible abolition of domination and violence can in principle no longer be separated from the struggle against the anti-Semitic delusion. When Adorno and Horkheimer write that the \"turnaround\" depends on \"whether the ruled become powerful in the face of absolute madness and put a stop to it, \"9 the ruled are no longer thought of only as a class or classes, but at the same time as individuals; the derivation is broken at a certain point and the functioning is viewed from the individuals, who can no longer be denied responsibility for it. In the face of that madness that has become abso- lute, critical theory itself has regained its concept of totality, which goes beyond mere sociological attribution and class affiliation, just as in the future no reflection on the abolition of domination will be possible for it without at the same time reflecting on the possible threat to the Jews."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "b36bea4de4009852",
      "text": "It is therefore not surprising that Horkheimer later persistently refused to republish the 1939 essay. Certain sections of it could be misunderstood as \"a rejection of Israel and the Jews in Germany themselves. \"10 Likewise, in 1961, he formulated another intellectual consequence to be drawn from The Jews and Europe, because the revolutionary possibility that essay believed it could directly envisage had been dementized by National Socialism: namely, that Zionism had been proven right. \"Herzl's book Der Judenstaat, which marks the beginning of the Zionist movement, embodies the doubt about the ability of European states to take the idea of pluralism seriously in the long run, that is, to leave the particular free to surrender to its own principle within the general. The Zionist movement, which no longer trusts the chance of pluralism of the culture of the autonomous individual in Europe, forms the simultaneously radical and resigned reaction of Judaism to the possibilities opened up in the last century. It is the bleakest aspect of the history that has taken place since then, the bleakest both for Judaism and for Europe, that Zionism was right. \"11 In a late letter, Horkheimer once again raises the \"difficult problem\" of \"uniting the state of Israel with the Jewish expectation of messianism\": he knows only one answer: \"that it first requires a 'practical solution'. \"12"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "f52d62ca555e7237",
      "text": "But the fact that for Critical Theory itself something like a practical field outside the directly Zionist objective and even before the founding of the Jewish state could come into view was only possible because the Western appeasement was now no longer continued, whatever the reasons underlying the new policy - and it was probably least of all the motive to prevent the extermination of the Jews themselves. In this respect, Horkheimer was hardly under any illusions throughout his life: \"Industrially advanced ... States, not to mention Stalinist Russia, did not wage war on Germany because of Hitler's terror, which they regarded as an internal affair, but for motives of power politics. \"13 But since the beginning of the war he felt compelled to distinguish between the powers in detail, depending on whether they practiced the terror themselves or not, and which of them - for reasons that were not of interest at first - could rather help to push it back. The powerlessness in the face of the impossibility to participate in a revolutionary action against any power politics was confronted with the compulsion for a practical solution in the defense against the worst - in this constellation only the 'metaphysical' foundations of the anti-Semitic madness and at the same time its own preconditions, the condition of the possibility of critique, were revealed to critical theory. Because it was recognized that such a solution was absolutely necessary, which was therefore no longer an aiming at merely supposed practice, something of these preconditions could emerge that had previously remained unexplained. To search for it without affirming this practice as legitimation of the existing is freely possible only if critique continues to \"relinquish the prejudice\" that \"some moment of the existing material reality is directly the positive\".14 It is precisely a matter of defending the presuppositions of critique, which cannot directly be the positive and must not be hypostatized as a positive standpoint, solely for the sake of the indirect possibility of critique, which, however, now coincides with the indirect defense against the politics of annihilation. Here, the experience of powerlessness may occur again and again with necessity: this experience guarantees that there is no such positive thing. If Horkheimer had once formulated that \"the totalitarian order is nothing else\" than \"its predecessor, which has lost its inhibitions, \"15 then he now recognizes that it is these inhibitions that can be important and names them, for example, as the \"power of resistance\" of law.16 He thus retrospectively agrees with those who have been criticized for their powerlessness. He thus retrospectively agrees with those whom he had so sharply criticized in The Jews and Europe, because they trusted that \"somewhere the reformation of Western capitalism is taking place more smoothly than that of German capitalism and that well-recommended foreigners still have a future\".17 Where this is really the case, where the power of resistance of law is still effective, is now unexpectedly part of the task of critical theory. "
    },
    {
      "type": "pagefold",
      "id": "a1cb7ab082af5bec",
      "text": "~"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "8aa9edb59b563dd0",
      "text": "With the engagement of critical theory in the was effort, the unresolved repression of political violence that still characterized the essay on the Jews and Europe found itself resolved in certain respects: Whoever does not want to speak of the state should also remain silent about capitalism. The blind spot, which was inherent in the concept of \"state capitalism\" and which was to recur and continue to have an effect in that of the \"administered world,\" is based on a certain conception of the solution of crises, which, as it were, could be managed domestically. Whatever was set in motion in the states as a reaction to the world economic crisis was to be brought to a common denominator in it, whereby some essential provisions of Marx's critique had to lose their immediate validity. One consequence of this was that at the Institute for Social Research the view actually prevailed that the international solidarity of the capitalist classes made war improbable18 - as if state capitalism, which prevailed over all, would already produce a globally ruling sovereign under whose wing the capitalists could, as it were, be unrestrainedly solida- ric among themselves; As if the war between the states, possible at any time, were not the essence of the state and therein the indispensable guarantor that in the states themselves accumulation in the capitalist mode can take place at all."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "6b97f4b385a0883a",
      "text": "The partisanship of the U.S. sovereign, on the other hand, implied a realization that not only restored Marx's insight into the connection between state and capital, but had to reach beyond it: that in Germany one was dealing not so much with another sovereign, but downright with a \"counter-sovereign\" (Manfred Dahlmann) - not Leviathan, but Behemoth. Students of Carl Schmitt, who understood how to turn doctrine against the teacher, who made their disappointment with Schmitt's behavior after 1933 productive in a radical critique of the latter's concept of the political, provided the essential impetus here to expose the blind spot in the talk of state capitalism and at the same time to relate Marx's concept of crisis to the state in a new way: Otto Kirchheimer and Franz Neumann."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "ffbc0dd725adb729",
      "text": "Just as Neumann, for example, denied a \"primacy of politics\" which the talk of state capitalism asserted and which should actually be called \"primacy of domestic politics\"; just as he wanted to prove that the state, even in this crisis in Germany, had absolutely no possibilities to simply abolish class rule and market mechanism domestically through planning, he himself came to quite different results than refutation and proof actually required. That the \"primacy of politics\" over economics was thus by no means established and could never be established within the boundaries of the nation-state, he tried to prove by means of empirical studies of the German economy and fundamentally doubted the stability of the Nazi system, convinced that the capitalist contradictions in Germany had to have an effect on a 'higher' level, even if they were concealed by a bureaucratic apparatus and Volksgemeinschafts propaganda; on a higher level meant: that they made war and ruthless expansion inevitable.19"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "615af1886c5ca4c0",
      "text": "But Neumann went beyond a classical Marxist presentation and took up, contre cœur, the moment of truth that the concept of state capitalism nevertheless contained, namely insofar as it held up the elimination of social forms of mediation in the form of the sphere of circulation as a characteristic of crisis politics. He took it up and radicalized it: Ultimately, it was questionable whether a formally or functionally uniform sovereign political power still existed in Germany at all. Accordingly, National Socialism should be understood not only as the abolition of the rule of law, but as a process in which its condition, the unified sovereign power, dissolves. Neumann spoke of the \"extreme formlessness\" to which this state was drifting, which as a result could no longer be called a state at all. Accordingly, one should rather speak of \"gangs\" - or to use Horkheimer's term: of \"rackets\" - whose leaders are constantly forced to get along again after disputes. In this respect, National Socialism no longer possesses a unified apparatus of coercion; it disintegrates into several political powers - Ernst Fraenkel had already characterized it in precisely this sense as a \"double state \"20 - which strike all the more brutally because their relations are not institutionalized, but are merely carried out personally. This personal unification, which is to be established ad hoc, can no longer be considered a unity in the sense of a state system, whether democracy or dictatorship: National Socialism, according to Neumann, was a non-state, an anarchy and a chaos."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "cc25bf009b7ea73a",
      "text": "Thus, the analysis revealed that, in contrast to fascism, this was a \"non-state,\" a totalitarian anarchy, so to speak, but Neumann avoided further raising the question of the unity of the process, i.e., the question of what took the place of the sovereign, i.e., what distinguished anarchy and chaos in the non-state from anarchy and chaos as such: he avoided speaking of the primacy of extermination. However, it says something about how far he was able to push the analysis when the first and most important study of the extermination of the European Jews was written by one of his students: Raul Hilberg took over from Neumann, as he himself sees it in retrospect, the notion of National Socialism as a \"non-state,\" where the \"ruling elites\" did not operate on a \"unified, rational basis, such as we associate with a legislature or a constitution.\" 21 At the same time, however, Hilberg speaks of a \"bias\" related to Neumann's Marxism: he had quite correctly analyzed Aryanization and the liquidation of Jewish property as a means by which the concentration tendencies of German industry were increased, but he could not then \"fully face the fact after all that the Jewish people were annihilated as such.\" 22 Hilberg took exactly this step - and necessarily the perspective was reversed: He viewed all processes from the \"German extermination efforts\", which he in turn knew to presuppose, and deduced from these efforts themselves the splitting of society into independent groupings as a necessity: As this process of extermination progressed, its requirements became more complex, it required a constantly growing number of authorities, party offices, business enterprises and military agencies to handle it.23 The extermination of the Jews, Hilberg writes, \"was a total process\"; the machinery necessary for it could not be distinguished \"fundamentally from the German social structure as a whole. "
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "f1bc6a4e24d59582",
      "text": "From this point of view, however, the dissolution of the monopoly of violence, as Neumann diagnosed it in National Socialism, the formulation itself of the \"non-state\", would have to be modified again. Thus, an organization like the SS gained a kind of permanently secured monopoly position in this structure, precisely because, on the one hand, it was the Schutzstaffel of the Führer, who embodied it, and, on the other hand, it occupied the key positions at the end of almost all processes of that machinery of extermination."
    },
