    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "dde47eafec8c17e7",
      "text": "To recall the ability of Critical Theory to resolve the blind spot of its own analysis is all the less a mere reminiscence, since this blind spot has defined the boundaries within which it is still received today: as a theory of the administered world - a world that can, so to speak, escape political power, i.e. the state, through administration. If, on the other hand, the inner contradictions, which in the history of Critical Theory showed themselves in the critique of the state and anti-Semitism, are not unfolded, if concepts such as that of the administered world are rather used to camouflage them, then the possibility is also lost of still \"empowering\" its experience in the sense of Walter Benjamin's thesis: how it \"flashes up in the moment of danger\". Flashing here means that always only the most abstract point of contact is to be fixed, the current threat is directly considered against the background of what Neumann once called Behemoth. But it is precisely the most abstract that proves to be immensely effective for the concrete analysis: on the one hand, the determination that society disintegrates into bands in the crisis and that, precisely in this, mediation through the spheres of circulation and law is eliminated, the rackets thus becoming the predominant form of the political; on the other hand, that unity in this disintegration in society and in the consciousness of it is only established through the imagination of a Jewish world conspiracy, in which mediation and circulation return distorted into a delusion."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "6da7bdff42fe8911",
      "text": "Of course, in the present conditions of the Middle East, where the danger is greatest that this imagination will be put into practice as the annihilation of the Jews, everything appears different at the same time. This concerns not only the possibilities of the rackets to make booty in the dissolution of circulation mechanisms and their relation to the world market and their position on it: they take on extremely diffe- rent forms in today's importance of oil production for the economy, depending on their respective starting position, which were unthinkable on the basis of the industrially highly developed and unified production in the Germany of the 1930s. Above all, it also concerns the ideological shape of the world conspiracy itself: Just as unity is established through a delusion of annihilation aimed primarily at a state, the state of the Jews, fantasized as a Jew among states, so the total process Hilberg spoke of, namely that the machinery necessary for annihilation could not be fundamentally distinguished from the German social fabric as a whole, Hilberg's view of the total process, namely that the machinery that was necessary for the destruction could not be fundamentally distinguished from the German social fabric as a whole, is to be understood in a different way insofar as the 'machinery' in which the Muslim Brotherhood in Egypt, Al-Qaeda and IS in Syria and Iraq, i.e. a multiplicity of jihadists on the borders of Israel, and the \"dual state\" of the Iranian regime work together, can no longer be distinguished from a religious fabric as a whole. Of course, this is no less a social phenomenon, insofar as all religion can only be understood as social, but part of the specificity of this phenomenon is that the clergy as well as the believers here successfully refuse from the outset to constitutionally and definitively separate politics and religion, public and private, as the sphere of circulation and the rule of law provide. Like National Socialism, Jihad no longer needs to hatch its own 'political religion', consciously deviating from the traditional Christian churches, in order to leave behind, both internally and externally, the boundaries of the state's form of rule, as they characterize the nation in its classical Western form. "
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "9180fcf0d81cf324",
      "text": "On the other hand, precisely that branch of Islam in which there is a clergy that itself exercises a direct political function and thus has religious leaders who can claim absolute authority for themselves also shows a special political quality in the expression of the racket principle that has become total: In its sphere, it is able to bring under control the rivalry of the rackets, which elsewhere are falling over each other in bloody gang wars; to give the religious structure stability and continuity, so that politics in the Shiite sphere of power-in this respect most reminiscent of that of National Socialism-still somehow builds on the old nation-state and yet, as a non-state, has long since transcended it25 and today, in the shape of the Islamic Republic of Iran, forms something like the organizing center of the threat that Israel faces."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "691f6db0e23cf25e",
      "text": "It is no coincidence that the relationship between the Revolutionary Guards and the regular military in Iran is reminiscent of that between the SS and the Wehrmacht on the most general level of comparative observation: There is no unification here, no subordination of one armed racket to the other, but rather both armies or organizations exist side by side - so that even in the case of the 'legitimate' military, one cannot speak of regulatory forces in the proper sense. Nevertheless, their rivalry is not fought out in armed forms, such as that between IS and Al-Qaeda in the 'civil wars' in Syria or Iraq. For there exists a 'spiritual leader', as the sole authority in supreme command - like Hitler in his day; and this leader is, in turn, only the 'positive' expression of having succeeded in imposing the primacy of annihilation to the extent that all rival rackets can be inte- grated and refrain from settling their conflicts by force. The priority of annihilation is aimed at Israel, and it is only in this way that the nuclear program has today acquired fundamental importance for the entire regime of the Islamic Republic - and also gives the Revolutionary Guards, again similar to the SS, a privileged role in the midst of the rival rackets, since, on the one hand, they are closest to the spiritual leader for whom they were created, and, on the other hand, they have the greatest importance for the finalization of the nuclear program, especially with regard to its military dimension. For in this program lies the potential to build the bomb with which the destruction of Israel, openly demanded by the regime since time immemorial, can be put into practice in the simplest way and beyond the Sunni and Shiite rackets of the Middle East fighting each other with extreme brutality."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "0b4b1d9c57da444d",
      "text": "On the other hand, Israel, after appeasement seems to have finally triumphed in the West, stands isolated, as if only this state, whose emergence was a consequence of the annihilation of the Jews, should still give a concept of what political violence can be, must be, in the face of the new Behemoth.26"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "9f92514a97ceef7b",
      "text": "Commitment to Israel must therefore follow the \"primacy of foreign policy\" - in the knowledge that it is by no means to be asserted as the primacy of the political against the capital relationship, but against the false one of domestic politics, which always only pretends the end of the crisis and the absence of violence in this relationship. To follow this primacy means nothing else than the interpretation and implementation of the practical imperative after Auschwitz; it is the mode of taking sides with the state of the Jews. This does not only mean to take it into account, for example, with regard to the assessment of the different political forces within Israel, depending on their foreign policy conceptions, but it means above all to judge each state according to its relationship to Israel and - in accordance with Israel's role for all Jews - to the Jews in its own country, especially when the conflicts escalate. In this context, primacy implies, first of all, countering in the most comprehensive way possible the phantasmagorias that are more than ever associated with international law. And here the legacy of Hobbes, in whom Leo Strauss recognized precisely that primacy (and against whom Carl Schmitt set his Großraumtheorie and his concept of nomos), gains immediate topical significance. For the idea that there would be a world domestic policy in which all foreign policy would merge, in which the relations of violence between states would be transformed into relations between peaceful democratic parties, i.e. peoples, has meanwhile become a fixed idea of the public sphere, especially of the European one. This development is exactly opposite to the earlier one of critical theory: its blind spot was not only not dissolved, but solemnly declared to be the central perspective. It is no coincidence, then, that that young assistant at the Institute for Social Research, whom Horkheimer once distrusted the most, now emerges as one of the leading European ideologists. The ghost speech that Jürgen Habermas is leading and on the content of which today all political commitment - from 'radical left' anti-imperialists to neo-Nazi big-space theorists - has sworn itself in, is based on the poisoned utopia that law could be asserted internationally in the same way as within a state - as if instead of the world revolution a single constitutional state could be established. The phantasmatic nature of this idea, in which the theories of Adorno laureates excel today, is already exposed by the simple realization that there is and can be no monopoly of force outside the states, which would guarantee the execution of this right. Between the states, each of which possesses the monopoly of force on their territories, the stronger among them is able to emerge temporarily as hegemon - like the USA in the western world, namely by the victory over National Socialist Germany -, but it can by no means rule over them as a sovereign. (Even within the Eurozone, today's Germany can only act as a hegemon in relation to the other states, although their sovereignty has been cut back considerably - admittedly also that of Germany, so that this state must partly 'play through the ranks' here: exercise its hegemonic power via the Brussels institutions). "
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "9005da5139ae6b30",
      "text": "It is part of the essence of international law that its principles, as well as all treaties between states, ultimately remain conventions that may or may not be observed depending on the respective balance of power among the states. This law consists ultimately of agreements and alliances, it is not a law covered by a superior and adequately armed power. As a system of conventions it is of no small importance, and it is not at all a question of denying this importance in general, since it offers in principle certain formal possibilities to settle conflicts peacefully or to steer them into more reasonable paths - but only if the balance of power between the states allows it, for instance if a hegemon or a hegemonic alliance is committed to its enforcement in a certain case. If this is the case, however, illusions are usually not far away, which place more trust in conventions than they deserve. Under the hegemony of the victorious powers of the First World War, the illusory trust in the League of Nations arose, counting on this international institution to prevent another world war. And it was probably connected with the blind spot of Critical Theory, with its concept of state capitalism, that it was so incapable of exposing this illusory trust as the mode of action of appeasement - the criticism of the behavior of the Jews, which Horkheimer made in the essay on The Jews and Europe, could even be interpreted as a substitute action for this urgent imperative."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "78935d00703a0fe7",
      "text": "Appeasement means nothing other than \"pacification\". However, such pacification is only possible in the long term within the state if a recognized monopoly on the use of force guarantees that the treaties between the citizens are valid: in this way, the citizens are able to refrain from the direct use of force in their relations. To demand this pacification between the states, on the other hand, proves to be a \"pious wish\" (Kant) in a very specific, structural sense, since the observance of the conventions and treaties depends solely on the currently prevailing balance of power among the individual states. The illusion, however, arises again and again from the need to deceive oneself about the fact that the form of the state itself, which makes pacification possible on the inside, has this latent state of war on the outside as its condition."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "ba4fc4f3c1ade105",
      "text": "Appeasement in the sense in which it was unmasked by National Socialism - so that this term, which even someone like Churchill used only affirmatively before 1938,27 can no longer be uttered by anyone today without at the same time recalling the shameful failure of the West - is thus always based on suppressing the relationship of violence between states; on suppressing the fact that the state, as a monopoly of violence and organized coercion that guarantees the accumulation of capital, is based on this relationship of violence. Appeasement is therefore the epitome of political engagement. By ignoring the essence of the state, one repeats in ideology what the unstate does in practice and promotes, knowingly or unknowingly, the disintegration of society and the state into rackets - which already includes giving international institutions, which by their very nature are all based on agreements between states, more importance than they can have."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "2cc34510e691b109",
      "text": "Such displacement may appear attractive in one form or another as utopia, like the Kantian idea of \"eternal peace,\" but to conceal the preconditions of state power and valid law in the process - despite Kant's own hesitation on this question - means a great danger, especially for the state of the Jews: Whoever recommends international treaties to Israel in the name of such a world domestic policy as an alternative for its own military potential - and this already includes the willingness to submit to the rules of the International Criminal Court of The Hague - wants, with this new, particularly opaque offer of assimilation to the Jews, basically to deprive their state of the sovereignty which alone protects it in case of emergency."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "94f8a65282780366",
      "text": "But Israel is not Ukraine, and all its relevant political forces will be careful not to act as the Ukrainian government did when it agreed in the 1994 Budapest Memorandum to give up its nuclear weapons in exchange for independence. For Israel's sovereignty means at the same time more than mere sovereignty, just as the loss of independence here means annihilation: its Law of Return of 1950 is directed at the emergency for every Jew, and that means not least: at the fact that even the really valid law within the other constitutional states can by no means adequately protect against worldwide anti-Semitism - even if these in crisis and state of emergency should not deprive their much-cited 'Jewish fellow citizens' of their civic rights. Unlike Israel, they do not have a special immigration law for all Jews. The special mention of the Jewish fellow citizens has become a common attitude in the constitutional state after the Shoah, but nothing has changed in their legal status in and between the states, nothing can change according to the general constitution of state rule and civil society - nothing except that now a separate, Jewish state exists with that special immigration right for all those affected by anti-Semitism. And this exposes every anti-Zionist ideology: it wants Jews to be as defenseless as the people in the kosher supermarket in Paris were in front of the assassin's rifle on January 9, 2015."
