      "item": {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "id": "6273f2387697cd4d",
        "text": "The moment of truth in these remarks is the warning against the appease- ment that the Western states had practiced toward Germany for so long and to which assimilating had to mean a catastrophe for the Jews. Gershom Scholem, who himself had suspected something of this catastrophe since his youth, nevertheless regarded Horkheimer's text as \"a wholly useless product\" - and in it a reprint of Marx's article on the Jewish question, as he told Benjamin, who had asked him for his opinion: The comparison with Marx's essay was not only obvious, but Horkheimer had wanted to write this essay again, mutatis mutandis, \"for the situation 100 years after Marx (which did not exactly put the wisdom of that - repugnant - essay in the brightest light, as much as it was fashionable to quote it at times).\" Obviously, Scholem reminded here the determination of the Jews to the sphere of circulation, which Horkheimer seems to base the need for assimilation, according to his diagnosis, on the \"self-interest\" and \"haggling\", in which the young Marx had seen the \"worldly reason and cultus of Judaism\". But in essence, his polemic is aimed at Horkheimer's complete failure to recognize the real situation of the Jews in the face of National Socialism. The adaptation of Marx's Jewish Question, he argues, as \"an encouragement to the Jews in the Second World War ... rat-less like ghost speech\".4 Thus, Horkheimer seemed to want to explicate his famous dictum: \"But whoever does not want to speak of capitalism should also be silent about fascism\" by addressing it to the Jews of all people: \"Practical adaptation may be inevitable for the individual, the concealment of the contrasts between the concept of man and capitalist reality deprives thinking of any truth. ... The confusion has become so general that the less truth aims at the supposed practice, the greater its practical dignity. \"5 Ghost speech could become that because the appeal not to desist from turning one's life to the preparation of the better presupposes what can no longer be presupposed at all for the Jews: to survive. Thus, if the practical adaptation of the individual in order to merely survive does not enter into thinking itself, the contrasts between the concept of man and capitalist reality become conceptual ghosts. Translated with www.DeepL.com/Translator (free version)"
