        "text": "In a letter to Adorno, Scholem was much more diplomatic about Horkheimer's essay, but wrote that he no longer believed \"that the social sciences had anything relevant to contribute\" on the subject of anti-Semitism. Horkheimer's essay also merely reinforced his conviction \"that here, unfortunately, only the metaphysicians have anything useful to say on the matter.\" 6 What Scholem meant here becomes clear in the passage from Horkheimer's essay, which states that the Jews \"as agents of circulation\" have been \"disempowered\" by the Fuehrer state because the modern structure of the economy puts the whole sphere largely out of course; they are therefore only \"hit as the first victims by the dictates of the rulers, who take over the function that has fallen out.\" Thus, the hatred of Jews belongs to the phase of fascist rise, but in the totalitarian order itself anti-Semitism will find a natural end.7"
