    {
      "type": "edit",
      "id": "1f3c194037ff96d5",
      "item": {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "id": "1f3c194037ff96d5",
        "text": "It is true that in the \"Elements of Anti-Semitism\" there is still the economistic derivation of anti-Semitism from the fact that the sphere of circulation is \"on the wane\"; likewise, it is reduced to a function for the fact that the \"ruled\" continue to affirm domination - and many a later speculative remark as to whether there are still anti-Semites or that hatred of the Jews could be replaced by hatred of any other population group may have its origin here. But derivation and reduction are now in a changed context. The perspective on the possible abolition of domination and violence can in principle no longer be separated from the struggle against the anti-Semitic delusion. When Adorno and Horkheimer write that the \"turnaround\" depends on \"whether the ruled become powerful in the face of absolute madness and put a stop to it, \"9 the ruled are no longer thought of only as a class or classes, but at the same time as individuals; the derivation is broken at a certain point and the functioning is viewed from the individuals, who can no longer be denied responsibility for it. In the face of that madness that has become abso- lute, critical theory itself has regained its concept of totality, which goes beyond mere sociological attribution and class affiliation, just as in the future no reflection on the abolition of domination will be possible for it without at the same time reflecting on the possible threat to the Jews."
