        "text": "It is therefore not surprising that Horkheimer later persistently refused to republish the 1939 essay. Certain sections of it could be misunderstood as \"a rejection of Israel and the Jews in Germany themselves. \"10 Likewise, in 1961, he formulated another intellectual consequence to be drawn from The Jews and Europe, because the revolutionary possibility that essay believed it could directly envisage had been de- mentized by National Socialism: namely, that Zionism had been proven right. \"Herzl's book Der Judenstaat, which marks the beginning of the Zionist movement, embodies the doubt about the ability of European states to take the idea of pluralism seriously in the long run, that is, to leave the particular free to surrender to its own principle within the general. The Zionist movement, which no longer trusts the chance of pluralism of the culture of the autonomous individual in Europe, forms the simultaneously radical and resigned reaction of Judaism to the possibilities opened up in the last century. It is the bleakest aspect of the history that has taken place since then, the bleakest both for Judaism and for Europe, that Zionism was right. \"11 In a late letter, Horkheimer once again raises the \"difficult problem\" of \"uniting the state of Israel with the Jewish expectation of messianism\": he knows only one answer: \"that it first requires a 'practical solution'. \"12"
