      "type": "edit",
      "id": "6b97f4b385a0883a",
      "item": {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "id": "6b97f4b385a0883a",
        "text": "The partisanship of the U.S. sovereign, on the other hand, implied a realization that not only restored Marx's insight into the connection between state and capital, but had to reach beyond it: that in Germany one was dealing not so much with another sovereign, but downright with a \"counter-sovereign\" (Manfred Dahlmann) - not Leviathan, but Behemoth. Students of Carl Schmitt, who understood how to turn doctrine against the teacher, who made their disappointment with Schmitt's behavior after 1933 productive in a radical critique of the latter's concept of the political, provided the essential impetus here to expose the blind spot in the talk of state capitalism and at the same time to relate Marx's concept of crisis to the state in a new way: Otto Kirchheimer and Franz Neumann."
