        "id": "cc25bf009b7ea73a",
        "text": "Thus, the analysis revealed that, in contrast to fascism, this was a \"non-state,\" a totalitarian anarchy, so to speak, but Neumann avoided further raising the question of the unity of the process, i.e., the question of what took the place of the sovereign, i.e., what distinguished anarchy and chaos in the non-state from anarchy and chaos as such: he avoided speaking of the primacy of extermination. However, it says something about how far he was able to push the analysis when the first and most important study of the extermination of the European Jews was written by one of his students: Raul Hilberg took over from Neumann, as he himself sees it in retrospect, the notion of National Socialism as a \"non-state,\" where the \"ruling elites\" did not operate on a \"unified, rational basis, such as we associate with a legislature or a constitution.\" 21 At the same time, however, Hilberg speaks of a \"bias\" related to Neumann's Marxism: he had quite correctly analyzed Aryanization and the liquidation of Jewish property as a means by which the concentration tendencies of German industry were increased, but he could not then \"fully face the fact after all that the Jewish people were annihilated as such.\" 22 Hilberg took exactly this step - and necessarily the perspective was reversed: He viewed all processes from the \"German extermination efforts\", which he in turn knew to presuppose, and deduced from these efforts themselves the splitting of society into independent groupings as a necessity: As this process of extermination progressed, its requirements became more complex, it required a constantly growing number of authorities, party offices, business enterprises and military agencies to handle it.23 The extermination of the Jews, Hilberg writes, \"was a total process\"; the machinery necessary for it could not be distinguished \"fundamentally from the German social structure as a whole. Translated with www.DeepL.com/Translator (free version)"
