      "item": {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "id": "9f92514a97ceef7b",
        "text": "Commitment to Israel must therefore follow the \"primacy of foreign policy\" - in the knowledge that it is by no means to be asserted as the primacy of the political against the capital relationship, but against the false one of domestic politics, which always only pretends the end of the crisis and the absence of violence in this relationship. To follow this primacy means nothing else than the interpretation and implementation of the practical imperative after Auschwitz; it is the mode of taking sides with the state of the Jews. This does not only mean to take it into account, for example, with regard to the assessment of the different political forces within Israel, depending on their foreign policy conceptions, but it means above all to judge each state according to its relationship to Israel and - in accordance with Israel's role for all Jews - to the Jews in its own country, especially when the conflicts escalate. In this context, primacy implies, first of all, countering in the most comprehensive way possible the phantasmagorias that are more than ever associated with international law. And here the legacy of Hobbes, in whom Leo Strauss recognized precisely that primacy (and against whom Carl Schmitt set his Großraumtheorie and his concept of nomos), gains immediate topical significance. For the idea that there would be a world domestic policy in which all foreign policy would merge, in which the relations of violence between states would be transformed into relations between peaceful democratic parties, i.e. peoples, has meanwhile become a fixed idea of the public sphere, especially of the European one. This development is exactly opposite to the earlier one of critical theory: its blind spot was not only not dissolved, but solemnly declared to be the central perspective. It is no coincidence, then, that that young assistant at the Institute for Social Research, whom Horkheimer once distrusted the most, now emerges as one of the leading European ideologists. The ghost speech that Jürgen Habermas is leading and on the content of which today all political commitment - from 'radical left' anti-imperialists to neo-Nazi big-space theorists - has sworn itself in, is based on the poisoned utopia that law could be asserted internationally in the same way as within a state - as if instead of the world revolution a single constitutional state could be established. The phantasmatic nature of this idea, in which the theories of Adorno laureates excel today, is already exposed by the simple realization that there is and can be no monopoly of force outside the states, which would guarantee the execution of this right. Between the states, each of which possesses the monopoly of force on their territories, the stronger among them is able to emerge temporarily as hegemon - like the USA in the western world, namely by the victory over National Socialist Germany -, but it can by no means rule over them as a sovereign. (Even within the Eurozone, today's Germany can only act as a hegemon in relation to the other states, although their sovereignty has been cut back considerably - admittedly also that of Germany, so that this state must partly 'play through the ranks' here: exercise its hegemonic power via the Brussels institutions). "
