      "id": "9005da5139ae6b30",
      "item": {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "id": "9005da5139ae6b30",
        "text": "It is part of the essence of international law that its principles, as well as all treaties between states, ultimately remain conventions that may or may not be observed depending on the respective balance of power among the states. This law consists ultimately of agreements and alliances, it is not a law covered by a superior and adequately armed power. As a system of conventions it is of no small importance, and it is not at all a question of denying this importance in general, since it offers in principle certain formal possibilities to settle conflicts peacefully or to steer them into more reasonable paths - but only if the balance of power between the states allows it, for instance if a hegemon or a hegemonic alliance is committed to its enforcement in a certain case. If this is the case, however, illusions are usually not far away, which place more trust in conventions than they deserve. Under the hegemony of the victorious powers of the First World War, the illusory trust in the League of Nations arose, counting on this international institution to prevent another world war. And it was probably connected with the blind spot of Critical Theory, with its concept of state capitalism, that it was so incapable of exposing this illusory trust as the mode of action of appeasement - the criticism of the behavior of the Jews, which Horkheimer made in the essay on The Jews and Europe, could even be interpreted as a substitute action for this urgent imperative."
